==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Limn
<hw>Limn</hw> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧m)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Limned</conjf> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧md)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Limning</conjf> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧m"n⟦icr⟧ng ⟦or⟧
l⟦icr⟧m"⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>limnen</ets>, fr.
<ets>luminen</ets>, for <ets>enluminen</ets>, F. <ets>enluminer</ets> to
illuminate, to limn, LL. <ets>illuminare</ets> to paint. ⟦root⟧122. See
<er>Illuminate</er>, <er>Luminous</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To draw
or paint; especially, to represent in an artistic way with pencil or
brush.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let a painter carelessly <qex>limn</qex> out a million of faces,
and you shall find them all different.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. Browne.
</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>To picture in words; to
describe in graphic terms.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To illumine, as books or parchments, with ornamental
figures, letters, or borders.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 855 pr=VMG --></p>

<p><ent>Limnaea</ent>⟦br⟧
